    "div",
    null,
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "This guide covers how to run and debug Ionic apps on iOS simulators and devices using ",
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "/docs/reference/glossary#capacitor"
        },
        "Capacitor"
      ],
      " or ",
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "/docs/reference/glossary#cordova"
        },
        "Cordova"
      ],
      ". iOS apps can only be developed on macOS with Xcode installed."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "There are two workflows for running Ionic apps on iOS:"
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "ul",
      null,
      " ",
      [
        "li",
        null,
        [
          "a",
          {
            "href": "#running-with-xcode"
          },
          "Running with Xcode"
        ]
      ],
      " ",
      [
        "li",
        null,
        [
          "a",
          {
            "href": "#running-with-the-ionic-cli"
          },
          "Running with the Ionic CLI"
        ]
      ],
      " "
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "The Xcode approach is generally more stable, but the Ionic CLI approach offers ",
      [
        "stencil-route-link",
        {
          "url": "/docs/reference/glossary#livereload"
        },
        "live-reload"
      ],
      " functionality."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "h2",
      {
        "id": "xcode-setup"
      },
      " ",
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "#xcode-setup"
        },
        "Xcode Setup"
      ],
      " "
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "https://developer.apple.com/xcode/"
        },
        "Xcode"
      ],
      " is the IDE for creating native iOS apps. It includes the iOS SDK and Xcode command-line tools. Xcode can be ",
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "https://developer.apple.com/download/"
        },
        "downloaded for free"
      ],
      " with an Apple account or it can be installed through the App Store."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "Once Xcode is installed, make sure the command-line tools are selected for use:"
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "docs-code",
      {
        "language": "shell"
      },
      " ",
      [
        "pre",
        null,
        [
          "code",
          null,
          [
            "span",
            {
              "class": "token prompt"
            },
            "$ "
          ],
          "xcode-select --install"
        ]
      ],
      " "
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "h3",
      {
        "id": "setting-up-a-development-team"
      },
      " ",
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "#setting-up-a-development-team"
        },
        "Setting up a Development Team"
      ],
      " "
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "All iOS apps must be code signed, even for development. Luckily, Xcode makes this easy with automatic code signing. The only prerequisite is an Apple ID."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "Open Xcode and navigate to ",
      [
        "strong",
        null,
        "Xcode"
      ],
      " » ",
      [
        "strong",
        null,
        "Preferences"
      ],
      " » ",
      [
        "strong",
        null,
        "Accounts"
      ],
      ". Add an Apple ID if none are listed. Once logged in, a Personal Team will appear in the team list of the Apple ID."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      [
        "img",
        {
          "src": "/docs/assets/img/installation/ios-xcode-accounts.png",
          "alt": "Xcode Accounts"
        }
      ]
    ],
    " ",
    [
